An interesting new feature in C# 3.0 is that of automatic properties on objects - this allows us to define a get/set property and the creation of the underlying field is taken care off for us.
We can therefore create a class like this:
public class Foo { public string Bar { get; set; } }  Now ignoring the fact that it&rsquo;s terrible OO to write a class like that, one thing that we&rsquo;ve been wondering is what&rsquo;s the difference between doing the above and just creating a public field on Foo called Bar like so:

Roy Osherove and several others have posted recently about introducing TDD to the &lsquo;masses&rsquo;
As I understand it Roy&rsquo;s idea is to separate the learning of TDD from the learning of good design principles - good design principles in this case being the OOP principles described in Uncle Bob&rsquo;s Agile Software Development Principles, Practices and Practices or on the Object Mentor website.
I am usually in favour of an approach that breaks a skill down into chunks so that it is easier to learn but in this case I feel that some of the big gains in coding in a TDD way is the decoupled design it encourages, which in my experience is more likely to follow good design principles.

One of my favourite features of IntelliJ is that it tracks the item that you currently have open on your Solution Explorer.
I thought this wasn&rsquo;t possible in Visual Studio and had resigned myself to trying to remember which project each file was in. Luckily for me a colleague pointed out that it is in fact possible but is just turned off by default.
Tools &gt; Options &gt; Projects and Solutions &gt; Check &lsquo;Track Active Item in Solution Explorer&rsquo;
